id="post-4407" class="post-4407 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-environment tag-canada tag-experimental-lakes-area tag-iisd tag-research"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/05/15/support-the-experimental-lakes-area/" title="Permalink to Support The Experimental Lakes Area" rel="bookmark">Support The Experimental Lakes Area</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/05/15 8:50 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/05/15/support-the-experimental-lakes-area/" title="Support The Experimental Lakes Area" rel="bookmark">2014/05/15 8:50 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/05/15/support-the-experimental-lakes-area/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p><iframe
width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/JBsTH28AV58" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p><iframe
src="https://www.indiegogo.com/project/world-s-leading-freshwater-research-facility-the-ela-needs-your-support/embedded" width="222px" height="445px" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" class="alignleft"></iframe></p><p>The Experimental Lakes Area has suffered greatly from the Canadian government&#8217;s anti-science funding policies and has luckily been saved by the <a
href="http://www.iisd.org/">International Institute for Sustainable Development</a>. To ensure that further damage can&#8217;t come from the ideologically-driven and anti-environment Conservative Party the ELA has turned to crowd funding to survive.</p><p>Last year, <a
href="http://thewalrus.ca/troubled-waters/">The Walrus magazine had a great article on the ELA</a> and how beneficial it is to science and the planet.</p><blockquote><p>You might have heard that the <a
href="http://www.iisd.org/">International Institute for Sustainable Development</a> (IISD) took it over the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) on April 1st. We are reaching out to the public to help make people feel is it “theirs” (and reduce reliance on government funding so it can’t be closed again due to changes in departmental policy)</p></blockquote><p>From their <a
href="http://igg.me/at/IISD-ELA/x/451321">Indiegogo page</a>:</p><blockquote><p>The ELA features a collection of 58 small lakes, as well as a facility with accommodations and laboratories. Since its establishment in 1968, ELA has become one of the world’s most influential freshwater research facilities. In part, this is because of the globally unique ability at ELA to undertake whole-ecosystem experiments.</p><p>There is nowhere else in the world that has the same potential to conduct this type of research and make such a positive impact on our world’s freshwater supplies.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://igg.me/at/IISD-ELA/x/451321">Support the campaign!</a></p><div
