id="post-4380" class="post-4380 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-environment tag-earth-day tag-internet tag-rallyware"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/04/22/transition-from-knowing-about-earth-day-to-acting-to-help-the-earth/" title="Permalink to Transition From Knowing About Earth Day to Acting to Help the Earth" rel="bookmark">Transition From Knowing About Earth Day to Acting to Help the Earth</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/04/22 9:16 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/04/22/transition-from-knowing-about-earth-day-to-acting-to-help-the-earth/" title="Transition From Knowing About Earth Day to Acting to Help the Earth" rel="bookmark">2014/04/22 9:16 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/04/22/transition-from-knowing-about-earth-day-to-acting-to-help-the-earth/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Today is <a
href="http://www.earthday.org">Earth Day</a> which is a day that calls people to be conscious of the environment and find ways to help or protect nature. It&#8217;s a great intuitive that has been around since 1970 and it&#8217;s impact continues to grow. One issue that a lot of environmental organizations run into is transitioning people&#8217;s knowledge of negative environmental behaviour into direct action.</p><p>This where a new web service called Rallyware can potentially help out. It looks alright and is one of many initiatives we&#8217;ve seen attempt this &#8211; hopefully this service will be a great success.</p><blockquote><p>According to Rallyware CEO both small and large environmental organizations miss out on important business goals because they don&#8217;t engage their online supporters, fans and followers with these four easy steps:</p><p>STEP #1:  CREATE BITE-SIZED TASKS<br
/> Create small, easy-to-accomplish offline tasks that must be checked off on the way to a bigger offline goal.</p><p>STEP #2:  TRACK PROGRESS ONLINE<br
/> Even though actions are occurring offline, online tracking allows everyone to know in real-time how they are performing.</p><p>STEP #3:  CREATE INCENTIVES<br
/> Motivate your supporters with physical rewards, status upgrades, and peer recognition for a job well done.</p><p>STEP #4:  ENGAGE AGAIN<br
/> Because the support of a follower or fan erodes with inactivity, always have the next set of tasks ready to go.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="www.rallyware.com">Rallyware&#8217;s website</a><br
/> <a
href="http://www.earthday.ca">Earth Day Canada</a><br
/> <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth_day">Earth Day on Wikipedia</a></p><div
